{"title_page": "Produce 101", "text_new": "{{short description|Reality television talent competition franchise}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{About|the Produce 101 franchise|the original South Korean TV series|Produce 101 (season 1)}}\n'''''Produce 101''''' is a [[reality television]] [[talent competition]] [[television franchise|franchise]] created by South Korean entertainment conglomerate [[CJ E&M]], based around the formation of a [[K-pop]] girl group or boy group. The format is noted for having no panel of judges, employing audience participation to make decisions, and for starting with a very large number of competitors, 101, narrowing that number down to a final 11. The franchise began in 2016 and has since expanded to [[China]] and [[Japan]].\n\nThe franchise has attracted a wide following in Asia. More than 10 million people cast votes during the finale of Season 2 in 2017, equivalent to a fifth of South Korea's population.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8031250/k-pop-audition-shows-produce-big-results-south-korea-music-industry|title=K-Pop Audition Shows Produce Big Results, But Cause Concerns Over Industry's Future|last=Herman|first=Tamar|date=2017-11-12|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref> In 2018, the eight episodes of [[Produce 101 (Chinese TV series)|''Produce 101 China'']] attracted more than 4.3 billion views on [[Tencent Video]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pandaily.com/produce-101-begins-a-wave-of-interest-in-chinese-idol-groups/|title=Produce 101 Begins a Wave of Interest in Chinese Idol Groups|date=2018-07-01|website=Pandaily|access-date=2019-04-23}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[Mnet vote manipulation investigation]], on November 14, 2019, producer Ahn Joon-young partially admitted to rigging the votes of all seasons of ''Produce 101'' during police questioning. He was arrested before over allegations of bribery and fraud in the franchise.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://koogle.tv/media/news/ahn-joon-young-admits-partially-to-vote-rigging-of-produce-101-season-1-2/|title=Ahn Joon Young Admits Partially to Vote Rigging of 'Produce 101' Season 1 & 2|last=|first=|date=November 14, 2019|work=KoogleTV|access-date=November 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Versions==\n===South Korea===\n* ''[[Produce 101 (season 1)|Produce 101]]'', featuring female trainees premiered on January 22, 2016.\n* ''[[Produce 101 (season 2)|Produce 101 Season 2]]'', featuring male trainees premiered on April 7, 2017.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Seoul staff|title=Citizen Producers|journal=[[Seoul (magazine)|Seoul]]|date=June 2017|issue=167|page=59|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8EQmDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA59|accessdate=16 April 2018|publisher=[[Seoul Selection]]|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite new|last1=Lee|first1=Mi-hyun|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5] '\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4 101' \uc2dc\uc98c2, 4\uc6d4 7\uc77c \uccab\ubc29\uc1a1\u2026\ucd1d 11\ubd80\uc791|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=241&aid=0002649063|website=Naver|publisher=Ilgan Sports|accessdate=March 23, 2017|language=ko|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822054146/http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=241&aid=0002649063|archive-date=August 22, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* ''[[Produce 48]]'', featuring female trainees premiered on June 15, 2018.<ref>{{cite new|title='\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4 48', \ub2e4\uc2dc \uc5ec\uc790\ub2e4\u2026 \u97d3\u65e5 \uc5f0\uc2b5\uc0dd \ubbf8\ud305 \uc2dc\uc791|url=http://entertain.naver.com/ranking/read?oid=241&aid=0002746543|website=Naver|publisher=Ilgan Sports|accessdate=January 16, 2018|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.insight.co.kr/newsRead.php?ArtNo=109253|title=Mnet '\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4101' \uc2dc\uc98c3 \uc5ec\uc790 \uc5f0\uc2b5\uc0dd \ud3b8 \ub0b4\ub144\uc5d0 \uccab\ubc29\uc1a1|website=\uc778\uc0ac\uc774\ud2b8|language=ko|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insight.co.kr/news/135471|title=Mnet '\ud504\ub4c0' \uc2dc\uc98c3 '\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a448' \uc5ec\uc790 \uc5f0\uc2b5\uc0dd \ud3b8 \uc62c\ud574 \uccab\ubc29\uc1a1|website=\uc778\uc0ac\uc774\ud2b8|language=ko|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref>\n* ''[[Produce X 101]]'', featuring male trainees premiered on May 3, 2019.<ref name=\"naver season 3 and 4\">{{Cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=109&aid=0003899189|script-title=ko:[\ub2e8\ub3c5] \"\uc6cc\ub108\uc6d0 \ub2e4\uc74c\uc740 \ub204\uad6c?\"\u2026'\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4101' \uc2dc\uc98c4, \ub0b4\ub144 4\uc6d4 \uccab\ubc29\uc1a1|website=entertain.naver.com|language=ko|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/ko-kr/entertainment/tv/%E2%80%98%ED%94%84%EB%A1%9C%EB%93%80%EC%8A%A448%E2%80%99-%EC%9D%B8%EC%8A%A4%ED%83%80-%E2%80%98%ED%94%84%EB%A1%9C%EB%93%80%EC%8A%A4101-%EC%8B%9C%EC%A6%8C4%E2%80%99-%ED%94%84%EB%A1%9C%EB%93%80%EC%8A%A4x101-%EC%98%88%EA%B3%A0-%EC%98%81%EC%83%81-%EA%B2%8C%EC%9E%AC/ar-BBQXDmD|title='\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a448' \uc778\uc2a4\ud0c0, '\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4101 \uc2dc\uc98c4'(\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4X101) \uc608\uace0 \uc601\uc0c1 \uac8c\uc7ac|website=MSN|language=ko-KR|access-date=2018-12-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181230181341/https://www.msn.com/ko-kr/entertainment/tv/%E2%80%98%ED%94%84%EB%A1%9C%EB%93%80%EC%8A%A448%E2%80%99-%EC%9D%B8%EC%8A%A4%ED%83%80-%E2%80%98%ED%94%84%EB%A1%9C%EB%93%80%EC%8A%A4101-%EC%8B%9C%EC%A6%8C4%E2%80%99-%ED%94%84%EB%A1%9C%EB%93%80%EC%8A%A4x101-%EC%98%88%EA%B3%A0-%EC%98%81%EC%83%81-%EA%B2%8C%EC%9E%AC/ar-BBQXDmD|archive-date=December 30, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===China===\n* [[Produce 101 (Chinese TV series)|''Produce 101 China'']], featuring female trainees premiered on April 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite new|title=Produce 101 China|url=http://www.hallyukstar.com/2018/01/31/tencent-making-produce-101-china/|website=Hallyu K Star|publisher=Hallyu K Star|accessdate=March 6, 2018|language=th}}</ref>\n* ''[[Produce Camp 2019]]'', featuring male trainees premiered on April 6, 2019.\n* ''[[Produce Camp 2020]]'', featuring female trainees premiered on Late April 2020.\n\n===Japan===\n* ''[[Produce 101 Japan]]'', featuring male trainees premiered on September 26, 2019.<ref>{{cite new|title=\u65e5\u672c\u7248\u300ePRODUCE 101\u300f\u59cb\u52d5 2020\u5e74\u30c7\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc\u306e\u30b0\u30ed\u30fc\u30d0\u30eb\u306a\u30dc\u30fc\u30a4\u30ba\u30b0\u30eb\u30fc\u30d7\u9078\u8003\u3078\n|url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2133376/full/|website=oricon|publisher=oricon|accessdate=April 11, 2019|language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite new|title=CJ ENM Announces New Show \u201cProduce 101 Japan\u201d|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/1316634wpp/cj-enm-announces-new-show-produce-101-japan|website=soompi|accessdate=April 11, 2019}}</ref> It will be represented by the country's 47 prefectures instead of the usual entertainment companies.\n* ''[[Produce 101 Japan Season 2]]'', featuring female trainees. It will be represented by the country's 47 prefectures instead of the usual entertainment companies.\n\n==Summary of shows by country==\nAs of 27 August 2019, there have been 7 groups debuted with 78 members involved in over 3 franchises of ''Produce 101''.\n\n:{{Color box|#90EE90|border=darkgray}} Currently airing\n:{{color box|#E0B0FF|border=darkgray}} An upcoming season\n:{{color box|#E0E0E0|border=darkgray}} Status unknown\n:{{Color box|pink|border=darkgray}} No longer airing\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%; line-height:18px; width:100%;\"\n|+\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\" | Country\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" width=\"11%\" | Local title\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" width=\"5%\" | Network\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" width=\"19%\" | Seasons and group created\n! colspan=\"3\" scope=\"col\" width=\"45%\" | Mentors\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\" width=\"10%\" | Hosts <br>{{small|(National Producer)}}\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"12%\" | Vocal\n! scope=\"c